<section xml:id="section-orthog-terminology" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p><dl>

	<li>
	<title>orthogonal vectors</title>
	<idx><h>orthogonal</h><h>vectors (in <m>\R^n</m>)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>orthogonal (in <m>\R^n</m>)</h></idx>
	<p>a pair of vectors whose dot product evaluates to <m>0</m></p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>normal vector (to a line or a plane)</title>
	<idx><h>normal vector</h></idx>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>normal</h></idx>
	<p>
	a vector that is orthogonal to the object of interest (<ie /> the line or plane being considered)
	</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>orthogonal projection (of a vector <m>\uvec{u}</m> onto a second vector <m>\uvec{a}</m>)</title>
	<idx><h>orthogonal</h><h>projection (onto a vector in <m>\R^n</m>)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>projection</h><h>onto a vector in <m>\R^n</m></h></idx>
	<p>
	the special scalar multiple of <m>\uvec{a}</m>,
	<md><mrow>
		\proj_{\uvec{a}}\uvec{u} \amp= k\uvec{a}, \amp
		\amp\text{where} \amp
		k \amp= \frac{\udotprod{u}{a}}{\unorm{a}^2};
	</mrow></md>
	sometimes called the
	<term>vector component of <m>\uvec{u}</m> parallel to <m>\uvec{a}</m></term>
	<idx><h>component</h><h>parallel (to a vector in <m>\R^n</m>)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>parallel</h><h>component (to a vector in <m>\R^n</m>)</h></idx>
	</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<p>
When the initial point of <m>\proj_{\uvec{a}}\uvec{u}</m> is placed at the origin, the terminal point will be the point closest to <m>\uvec{u}</m> on the line passing through the origin and parallel to <m>\uvec{a}</m>.
</p>

<image width="58%">
	<!-- description gets inserted as alt text in html img tag -->
	<description>Diagram of an orthogonal projection.</description>
	<latex-image><xi:include href="terminology.d/proj.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
</image>

<p><dl>

	<li>
	<title>vector component of a vector <m>\uvec{u}</m> orthogonal to a second vector <m>\uvec{a}</m></title>
	<idx><h>orthogonal</h><h>component (to a vector in <m>\R^n</m>)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>component</h><h>orthogonal (to a vector in <m>\R^n</m>)</h></idx>
	<p>the vector <m>\uvec{u} - \proj_{\uvec{a}}\uvec{u}</m></p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<p>
When the initial point of the vector <m>\uvec{u} - \proj_{\uvec{a}}\uvec{u}</m> is placed at the terminal point of <m>\proj_{\uvec{a}}\uvec{u}</m>,
it points towards the terminal point of <m>\uvec{u}</m>,
at a right angle to the line that passes through the origin and is parallel to <m>\uvec{a}</m>.
(See the diagram above.)
</p>

<p><dl>

	<li>
	<title>point-normal form (of a line in <m>\R^2</m>)</title>
	<idx><h>point-normal form</h><h>for a line</h></idx>
	<p>
	the vector equation <m>\dotprod{\uvec{n}}{(\uvec{x} - \uvec{x}_0)} = 0</m>,
	where <m>\uvec{x}_0</m> is a vector from the origin to a known point on the line,
	<m>\uvec{n}</m> is a known normal vector for the line,
	and <m>\uvec{x}</m> is a variable vector representing an arbitrary point on the line (again as a vector from the origin)
	</p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title>cross product (of vectors <m>\uvec{u}</m> and <m>\uvec{v}</m> in <m>\R^3</m>)</title>
	<idx><h>cross product</h></idx>
	<idx><h>vector</h><h>cross product</h></idx>
	<p>a particular vector in <m>R^3</m> that is orthogonal to both <m>\uvec{u}</m> and <m>\uvec{v}</m>; written <m>\ucrossprod{u}{v}</m></p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

</section>
